,Recommended,299720,17242979,"Posted: 26 July, 2015",all,b e a r d h a m m e r,"WOW.  This game's awesome.  Concept's the same as all other TD games, the little creeps that you have to kill travel on a set path, and you have several fixed tower positions.  But the awesome thing is that you're able to build base blocks with MORE tower spots on them.  So let's say on a map, you've got just one tower spot to build on.  You could put a cube-shaped base block on that spot, giving you five more build spots on that block (top and the 4 sides).  On top of that cube, you could put ANOTHER cube-shaped base block, so now you've got 8 sides and 1 top build spot.*[1]  So far, I've seen the cube-shaped base block and a triangle-shaped base block, not sure if there are more to come, but with just these two, the possibilities are endless.The turrets, I have yet to get the hang of.  Sometimes I'll place a turret in a spot and think it's gonna fire and be very effective, but it just won't function at all.*[2]  But, if you build to check out the turret's firing distance/directions, and then sell BEFORE you start the round, the tower/baseblock sells for full price.  You're always getting XP and unlocking stuff, too, so losing doesn't even feel terrible.  Feels almost like I'm MORE encouraged to play as I lose, making mistakes is rewarding me with more skill.  I dunno, I love it so far.There's maybe a half hour learning curve.*[3]  The camera's tough to get the hang of at first, the UI's really barebones, and I'm not able to find a controls section (probably isn't one), but if it's possible to rotate the base blocks, I definitely want to know how.  Also turned the music off -immediately- because no sir.  Developers, if you're reading this, I can compose a far better soundtrack for you, or just let you use an instrumental album I've already written/recorded.I just can't stress enough how great the gameplay is.  Anything in this review that even sounds remotely like a drawback, it's a minor gripe that I honestly don't care about.  Bells and whistles can go to hell.  The strategy in this game is second to none.*[4]8.5/10.  Maybe a 9.  I'd give it a 10 if it came with flashier graphics (I'm picturing RUSH meets Defense Grid 2), the ability to rotate base blocks, an easier camera, and a pause button.  Took me 20 minutes to know I'll be playing this game for years to come.  Basic UI, basic graphics, and GENIUS, spectacular, limitless gameplay.July 20, 2017 Edit - I'd like to follow up on the starred and numbered statements in my original review.*[1] - The base blocks are a HUGE part of this game (to me, at least), in two massive ways.  One is that creative base block stacking and angling (which, the possibilities are truly endless) can provide you with turret build spots that maximize a turret's functionality.  One cleverly-place build spot can allow one turret to attack the enemy's path three or four different times.  Sometimes, I will stack twenty blocks to get a weird 45-degree angle overhang build spot because it can use 100% of a turret's range and get me through a ton of waves so I can save my money and be effective towards the very end.*[2] - It took a while for me to grasp the feel of turret ranges, prioritization, and firing speeds.  If a turret ever didn't function for me, it was because I was forgetting that turrets can't look down (only 360 degrees around them and up).  Like, if you cut the Earth in half along the equator, and you put a turret right in the center, it would only be able to fire ALONG the equator and north of it, never below.  And sometimes, a turret's targeting priority can make it less effective.  If you have your first turret set to attack the strongest enemy, and five of equal strength go walking past, it's going to fire at the first one, retarget the second one (because it is now the strongest) and fire, retarget the third one, and so on.  All of that time it takes to spin and aim at a new target, it's inefficient.  But prioritization solves that.*[3] - Half hour learning curve to start feeling at home and making some strong progress.  But, 100 hours of play still won't let you master the game.  You will always be strategizing and getting better.  Learning curve's low, but the skill ceiling is sky high.*[4] - SECOND. TO. NONE."
